<DOC><DOCNO> AP890424-0212 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 0646EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     04-24 0654</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0682</SECOND><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Lane Kirkland sees the ``sanctification ofgreed'' he attributes to the Reagan years beginning to crumble,bringing favorable winds to the sails of the movement he oftenrefers to as a ship.   ``I think there is perhaps the beginning of some change inclimate,'' the AFL-CIO president said in an interview last week.``We've been beating against some fairly strong winds, but I thinkthe ship is sound and seaworthy. And winds change.''   His is a view cautiously shared by other labor leaders, who inrecent weeks have found themselves awash with good news, a raretiding in a decade the American labor movement would prefer toforget.   Few labor leaders expect a sudden turnaround of the decline ofthe 1980s, during which membership in unions has dropped by 3million to 17 million and the percentage of workers who are unionmembers dropped from 23 percent in 1980 to 16.8 percent last year.   But many believe the passing of the Reagan administration andlabor's recent high profile may help unions halt their slide andimprove their public standing.   ``I think the American people are listening to what we aresaying and, yes, I think things are progressing,'' United AutoWorkers President Owen Bieber said.</TEXT><DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Tens of thousands of students at Beijing'suniversities went on strike today, calling for democracy, humanrights and a free press in the largest student boycott in CommunistChina's history.   At Beijing University, the country's most prestigious, studentsfor the first time produced an independent newspaper.   The class boycott today brought into a new phase pro-democracyprotests that were sparked by the April 15 death of oustedCommunist Party chief Hu Yaobang, a popular reformer.   Posters calling on students to strike, satirical cartoons ofgovernment leaders, and essays decrying official corruption coveredthe walls of many universities throughout Beijing.</TEXT><DATELINE>ROCKY BOY, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   More than a century after frontier warsceased on the plains and valleys of Montana, Indians are embroiledin a new battle for independence against the federal government.   On the Rocky Boys Indian Reservation in north-central Montana, atribal prosecutor has filed criminal charges against the chiefagent of the Bureau of Indian Affairs, accusing him of interferingin tribal affairs by threatening not to recognize an elected tribalgovernment.   The case has implications nationwide for Indian tribes' power tocontrol their own governments and reservations.   ``My whole idea in this thing was, `How much authority does thisguy have?''' said Chippewa-Cree Tribal Prosecutor Jim Morsette.``This is a problem not only in Rocky Boy, but on all thereservations.''</TEXT><DATELINE>WAPATO, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   In central Washington's Yakima Valley,where fruit trees bloom in blazing sunshine, fear has taken rootbecause of an outbreak of a contagious disease that has killed sixpeople this year.   Twenty people, including four infants, have become ill withmeningococcal bacteria, which can lead to meningitis and otherillnesses.   Doctors are swamped, firefighters worried about givingmouth-to-mouth resuscitation, parents pulled their children out ofpreschools, and about 18,000 people have been vaccinated.   The greatest worry is that there is no effective vaccine,therefore no protection, for children under age 1.</TEXT><DATELINE>MAAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The carcasses of burnt cars and shatteredwindow frames are being swept off the streets of Jordan'sriot-swept southern towns.   People say the anger vented in four days of violence last weekto protest government-imposed austerity measures will not disappearso easily.   Jordan has in recent years escaped most of the Middle East'sturmoil so last week's outbreak of discontent _ from people who forgenerations have been the monarchy's staunchest loyalists _ came asa shock.   ``The rioters want things to get better in Jordan,'' said a25-year-old man from the city of Kerak who said he was among thestone-throwers who attacked government buildings and banks.</TEXT></DOC>